< text>
Kind of pricey but it is cleaned daily and they run ceiling fans and AC when needed so I stopped going to the sweat shop laundromats. Most employees are friendly and helpful (there's always one or two in every bunch that aren't) the TV's usually have something decently entertaining on if you like to watch it.
They do have dryer specials what I don't like is people come out if the bush that have not washed their clothes there with 7-10 loads right as my laundry is just about to come out of the washer and they take up 7-10 dryers to take advantage of the dryer special. That is not right or fair to loyal customers that do both wash and dry there. I am a twice a week customer that does not even try to come on those days because of the rude dryer hog people that get away with doing that. This happens at all Grande locations and no one says a word to the dryer takeover people.  I just go elsewhere if I need to do my laundry on their dryer special days.This is why I'm rating 4* I was thinking of giving 3* because it pisses me off.<//text>

Jupiter Devours- Maelynn Le<//username>
< Date>
1614538664391<//Date>
<UserId.>109011699302249023791<//UserId.>< Rating>
4</Rating>
<pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPKUBEBNj84gFrcX61a7GmY-oDcUhumU8pP0OQ-=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNlpu4awr9ueKYn6PwKQvsLJUgXv5wWlJYaqJx9=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNexrBqvFf4I8LRJKneWbqFhVXZjN9ftVAd_64X=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipN4SQX87DvPZiqMnBmNOEULf8F84V-hF93XTuhr=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pics>< Text>
Little by Little is a true hidden gem at the Warm Springs district in Fremont, CA, close to where T4 is. They are tucked away in the corner of the shopping center and this place serves really delicious food! They currently only do to go orders only and all the staff members do their very best to maintain covid safety procedures. They do fusions of every cuisines and serve from pastas, sandwiches, rice plates, and sides. I really enjoyed their food so much that I 100% truly recommend the most! I got to try their vegetarian options which were the roasted garlic cauliflower truffle Mac and cheese, the rainbow salad, and mushroom coconut pesto curry.

I will review the roasted garlic cauliflower truffle Mac and cheese first! It was absolutely my favorite dish on the menu! The presentation of the Mac and cheese was beautiful with the breadcrumbs on top and the chives to give it a nice color. Literally I haven‚Äôt had Mac and cheese in so long and this brings back many memories but I liked this version MUCH BETTER! I love the addition of the truffle oil because I think it gave a nice fattiness to the dish but it wasn‚Äôt drenched in oil which that‚Äôs a good thing. The breadcrumbs gave the Mac and cheese great texture and I love the dish having some garlic as well. I actually do wish that the Mac and cheese was cheesier because Mac and cheese is supposed to be a cheesy dish and for me, I personally wanted more cheese not only to make a viral tik tok video but taste wise, I would have liked and tasted more cheese. I also didn‚Äôt see a lot of cauliflower unless it was cut up small which I appreciate so you don‚Äôt get huge chunks but I didn‚Äôt  taste cauliflower. Overall, my favorite dish on the menu hands down, I really recommend the Mac and cheese!

The rainbow salad is basically kale, baby spinach, red quinoa, cherry tomatoes, red cabbage, roasted white corn, crispy quinoa, with yuzu aioli, and gribiche sauce on the side. This was truly a rainbow salad! I saw a lot of color and the presentation of the salad was beautifully done! You get the freshness of the kale, spinach and love all the vegetables and fruits in the salad as well! The nuttiness of the quinoa was delicious which added a nice flavor aspect to the salad. On the dressing, I‚Äôm questioning why I got two dressings because normally  we would only see one dressing so the dressings don‚Äôt clash. I wish I only got one dressing instead of two different dressings but both of them tasted about the same in terms of flavor. If I were to choose, I feel like the yuzu aioli was better in terms of flavor and thickness. I thought the gribiche sauce was too thick for me but the yuzu aioli felt lighter; still a but thick but tasted better in my opinion.

The mushroom coconut pesto curry has button mushrooms, red quinoas, cauliflower, corn, and garlic rice. I loved the flavor of the coconut curry. I thought it was creamy, smooth, light, and it was mild. I also love the addition to the quinoa because that added flavor and texture. The mushrooms, I love too and that is like a substitute for meat so the seasoning was on point and definitely was fulling to eat. With the cauliflower, again I didn‚Äôt get a lot of cauliflower. I wish there was more and I wish the rice had more garlic because I didn‚Äôt get a lot of garlic. Overall, I‚Äôm super satisfied with this curry and loved all the elements of the curry!

Overall, Little by Little in Fremont is a true hidden gem in Fremont! I really recommend it and please support this business! They have put a lot of heart and soul to the food and the chef was great in putting everything together to make the dish perfect!<//Text>

<text>What a hidden gem in Warm Springs. I have passed by this place for so many times without notice it.

We decided to give it a try on a beautiful weekend. Small restaurant but completely filled up on Saturday noon.

The food here is so delicious and the drinks are cute too.

Order:
Roast Bone Marrow: Personally I love the bone marrow a lot, and the sauce on the side is phenomenal.

Confit duck leg: Love the harmony of crispy duck skin and the tender duck meat!

Drinks:
Rose lemonade is delicious!

Thanks for the complimentary spiced popcorn and definitely come back next time to explore more options.< /text>< pics>

<Review>It's about time Fremont gains a new restaurant with class.

The core cuisine is American & French tapas. The menu is subject to change and it's been suggested that foie gras might be served in the future.

The most notable items I had here was the bone marrow, short rib, and uni pasta.

The bone marrow is served with some bread and it's basically a pate. Very rich and flavorful, would be a great choice if you're looking for brunch.

The short rib's presentation is lovely, like a meadow encircled by a dark forest. The meat just falls apart with a slight push of the fork. The garnish adds a complexity to the meat's succulent texture and a small bite of the salad followed by the meat helps balance the flavors. It is by far my favorite dish as it is both a feast for the eyes and the mouth.

The uni pasta here is sure to convince anyone apprehensive of trying uni. The uni itself turns the dish practically into macaroni and cheese, but it doesn't have the smell or heaviness of cheese. The uni is light and custardy and goes great with the roe on top of the pasta. It almost tastes like a comfort food, but has the flavors of the sea incorporated into it. Definitely recommended.

Will come back soon to see how the menu evolves.<//Review>< date>

<user_id>107651363527543844794<//user_id>< username>
Jonas Gebhardt</username>
< time>
1524431783413<//time>
< Rate>
3<//Rate>
< review>
I came here for date night on a Friday evening without a reservation. I've learned that I should make a reservation next time in order to secure one of the few tables.

I ended up sitting by the bar which is not bad in any way as you get a good view on the kitchen and can see how everything is being prepared. I observed how the chef takes great pride in finishing off every dish before he sends it out and is focused on quality and a consistent experience.

Having that said, the dishes do look pretty and very presentable. I tried 4 dishes, plus desert and every dish was worth a photo. The first one I had was the Octopus dish. It's supposed to be a shareable dish, but the portion is still rather small and you only get a few bites of Octopus. All of that is fine in general, the issue is the prize. You pay over $20 for that dish and if you want to feed two people well, you need to order at least three more dishes - if not even four more. This means you will end up paying between $100-170 including drinks. I am ok to pay this kind of money for a nice dinner, but I expect the right service and taste then. Let me elaborate on this.

All dishes I had tasted solid, but there was nothing that really blew me away. Some dishes, like the Risotto are a great idea, but the flavor is not yet there where it needs to be. It felt too salty to me and too soft. I think it's a matter of time and the chef will turn this into a great dish.

Similar with the bone marrow. It's something that you don't eat every day and it was certainly well cooked. But it was missing that certain something that makes me want to end up spending so much money on it. For example, it comes with basic toast which feels just very boring.

The short ribs were solid as well, but not tender and juicy enough for the prize.

Again, there's nothing wrong with the food, but I think the chef just needs some time to refine and work on the recipes to justify the high charge.

The service was so-so. I've ordered a glass of the Cabernet from Passo Robles. One of my favorite wine regions and the red did not disappoint. But: they charge $12 a glass which is somewhat standard in the Bay area, but I never got poured less wine in a glass than here. It almost felt I get more wine when I go to a wine tasting. When I tried to bring this up with the waiter in a friendly and funny way and told him that I love this wine, he just mentioned he would let the chef know. I also asked if the Yelp check-in for 50% off cocktails would apply to wine, because I would take another glass if it would - he said no. I had two sips of the wine and the glass was empty. When I paid and was ready to leave, the waiter offered me another glass on the house - very wrong timing.

Overall the service was very friendly though and I ended up leaving a nice tip.

The place itself feels upscale, modern and cool. It could almost be in L.A. I feel it has huge potential but requires some serious work on the food, the prizes and the wine.</review>

< Name>
Ryan Pearson< /Name>
<Review>Travel Transparency in itself is a cool business idea. They do require an up-front cost, ranging from $3k - $10k, to basically give you membership and access to discounted hotels, time shares, houses etc. . . Sometimes the price for a full week (for a hotel or time share) is around $200. This is an insanely good deal.

There's a yearly fee of $150, and if there wasn't a $3k initial investment my wife and I would have jumped on it. This private membership does offer some great prices on vacations. So the initial investment ($3k - $10k) could make A LOT of sense, and save you a lot of money if you're going to travel a good amount.

My issue is mostly with their marketing company. They got my wife and I to show up. So kudos to that. They did their job. But we asked several times about the details of the "round trip airfare". We were told we won free tickets from Delta and could fly anywhere in the continental US. We asked about restrictions and the marketing company said we would receive an email with all details. The email we got just further highlighted that we would get 2 round trip tickets and 2 nights in a hotel! Sounds great right? **Terms and conditions apply** But they do charge $75/person in gov't fees and $75/person in a "reservation fee". We thought, "ok, if we can fly from San Diego to New York for $150/person, that's still pretty good". Because of this, we went through the presentation, which was well done. Very nice people. No complaints in the presentation. I just wish they would have told us about the flight restrictions up front.

After the presentation we get our "voucher" for the plane tickets:

**Valid for Monday, Tuesday or Wednesday Departure dates only**
**you are required to send $100 cashiers check to CasablancaExpress to request your travel dates**
** The $100 cashiers check is refundable 30 days AFTER you complete your travel**
**After Casablanca gets your $100 cashiers check. They send you a reservation letter that you must complete with your requested departure dates. You must send this back with $75/person reservation fee**
**You must provide THREE different departure dates at least 60 days in advance of your first date and 30 days between subsequent dates**
**You must provide at least one alternate destination**
**All reservations are subject to availability**

These last few qualifications makes planning a trip really hard. This makes me assume that CasablancaExpress (who you're sending $100 to, then $75/person to) gets to pick any of the 3 dates (within a 3 month range) that you provided, and either to your preferred destination OR the backup destination?? I'm assuming they will just pick the worst/cheapest date, and the cheaper destination.

Departing flights are between 3-10 and return flights are between 6am - 1.

Your tickets will be mailed at least 10 days prior to your arrival date. . .

All of this would have been good to know BEFORE agreeing to the meeting. This is what should have been provided in the email. I understand that Travel Transparency can kinda blame this on "their marketing companies" But if they don't know what their marketing companies are telling their future customers, theres a little bit of blame on Travel Transparency for that. . .

For a company called travel TRANSPARENCY, this was not a good start to doing business with them.

The flight/hotel deal has wayyy too many *send me money first by mail cashiers check* *send me more money by mail with 3 different dates that they get to choose* -- WAY TOO COMPLICATED for a company who is trying to make travel easier by just going online and booking a vacation. I feel like their promotion should be in-line with their business model. Not something that will be extremely hard to plan around (what am I suppose to ask my boss for 3 different travel dates for 3 subsequent months and be like "yeah boss sorry, I'm going on a vacation, but i dont know when yet, can i get march 3-7, april 3-7 and May 3-7 off please?".)

I wish the business success because I like the business model. They need to change their marketing plan<//Review></record>

<Rate>2<//Rate><text>These guys are a wreck. I called looking for a specific tree, which they reported to have. I drove across town to buy it, and was told that, no, the tree I wanted was at their other location on La Sierra, about a mile from where I was when I had called.

So I opened up Google Maps to look for the location on La Sierra, but it doesn't exist on the map. So I went back in to get directions/ address, and they pulled out a handy, pre-printed, laminated map to look at, which they easily could have given me at first. After studying the map, I observed that the La Sierra location is not in fact on La Sierra, but is instead on Campbell. Which they didn't tell me.

So I programmed in the address, and crossed town again, only to find a locked gate and no one around. The place looked closed. After wandering around for 20 minutes, and figuring out that the gate was not actually locked, I found a worker, who informed me that the tree I wanted was at ANOTHER location over off of a different street (Norwood). So I followed him on a quarter-mile walk to the other site, where he escorted me to the tree I had requested... only to find that it was a DWARF version of the tree. They had no standard-size trees in the variety that I had requested.

So after driving across town twice, and wasting 2 hours trying to get what I wanted, they didn't have the thing they told me that they had.

The only reason I'm giving them 2 stars is because the worker who helped me locate the (wrong) tree was helpful and sympathetic, noting that the guys at the Dufferin location often misstate their stock, don't verify availability, and don't give clear directions to customers. So while it didn't help me at all, at least he understood my situation.

This could all have been avoided with some very minimal customer service effort on their part, saving me hours of wasted time, and a lot of driving. But they don't seem to really care about their customers, so I won't be back. I recommend to you that if you want something from them, be very specific with them about exactly what it is that you want, and make sure you ask where you should expect to find it. Otherwise you may end up on the same wild goose chase that I experienced.

Consider yourself warned.</text><Pics>None< /Pics><Resp>None<//Resp><Gmap_id>0x80dcb0135194d9db:0x517a96a3a4e7d666</Gmap_id></record>

<Review>If I had to submit a one-sentence review of the Security & Firearms Training Academy (SAFTA) located at 3355 Myrtle Avenue #200 North Highlands, CA 95660then it would be:

During our 80-hour Advanced Security Officer Course, the staff at SAFTA provided quality hands-on training and relevant academic instruction that sets up graduates for success as a security guard professional.

In addition to my one sentence review of SAFTA, I would like to also say that SAFTA is staffed with security guard professionals that care about instilling pride and standards in the security guard profession.  SAFTA training stressed the importance of proper application of escalation of force.  SAFTA instructors focused on teaching the bedrock fundamentals and skills that are needed for working as a security guard.  Trainers focused steadfastly on safety during the firearms and baton training and certification.  I highly advise that people interested in becoming a security guard take courses of instruction from SAFTA.

A special note on two integral members of SAFTA:

Ed ‚ÄúGunny‚Äù Caballero is the subject matter expert who taught our class and his teaching style may be gruff like a drill sergeant at military basic training, but it was comfortably familiar and I think necessary.  Why?  Because the split second decisions that a security guard might have to make could be the difference between life and death and between criminal and civil courts of justice.  The class needed to have a strong foundation of knowledge and training related to penal codes and proper use of force.  Gunny provided us that expert instruction.

Sherryann is the mother that all of us wished were our own.  I cannot think of a more beautiful woman or soul. <userid>100401904906302998049</userid><user_name>G Gepulle<//user_name><date>1553477188672< /date><Rating>5< /Rating>< Text>
I took my 16 hour CCW course here and I am glad that I did. When I was shopping around for a course, this place compared to others was cheaper. But that is not the only good thing about this place. This class was very informational and was taught by a very experienced instructor: Steve Caballero, ED.D. This guys is a retired Marine who has plenty of experience with working as law enforcement. He takes his job very seriously because he knows he was given the responsibility to train civilians to have a concealed carry licensed. He teaches you when is a right time to draw you weapon and teaches you all the steps that you need to consider before drawing your weapon. And he stated that within the 40 years of working in law enforcement, he only had to draw his weapon twice and had to shoot it only once. So he knows the importance of when it is a right time to draw you weapon. He is very stern but only because he wants to assure that we are all being safe. JC who deals with all the paper work is a nice lady and has awesome customer service. This course is very informational and I recommend this to anyone who has to take the 16 hour course or renewal. I will be back in two years to renew. Thank you SAFTA!< /Text>

<rating>5< /rating>< text>
As a security company that is always looking for new guards, we always start with SAFTA. The staff here are very knowledgeable and professional and always keep us up to date with new candidates. A lot of our security guards have come from here, already trained, eager, and ready to learn more. JC and her team of instructors really care about their students and go above and beyond for them. < Review>
The professionalism and wealth of knowledge that SAFTA provides is unparalleled. They are unequivocal in their approach and have numerous classes and training seminars designed to help empower people to become self-reliant and able to defend themselves if need arises. I took their CCW course over the span of a weekend and learned so much great information that I kept gleaning over for week's after the course. The instructor, kindly referred to as "Gunny", took as much time as we needed to instruct us in a tactful and skilled manner. We learned so many hands-on techniques, combined with classroom information on what is and is not allowed according to the rule of law.

He and all of SAFTA also made sure that we were comfortable (which was great for the ladies in the room) and not intimidated by what some would consider an intimidating course/topic. Overall, I feel exponentially more capable now to be able to defend myself if need arises, and to share with others just how to stay safe in an ever-increasingly dangerous world.  I am certain that because of the training I received at SAFTA,  I am a more responsible citizen - as are other members of my family who took the course with me.

I highly recommend SAFTA for all your training and safety needs. You will learn more than you ever imagined, and have the confidence and empowerment you need to stay safe in your personal and work endeavors.

Thank you SAFTA!

Sincerely,

<Review>Friday afternoon 4:00 I leave my house to go coach my club volleyball team, my scion xb still parked in front of my house. I had paid DMV for a Non-Op on the vehicle because of a blown engine. When I get home at 8:30pm I noticed my car gone. I go inside and ask my wife if they saw anything happen to it. I check with my neighbors nothing. I call Ontario PD about 8:45pm to report my car stolen. The lady on the phone, after looking up the license plate number tells me it was towed because a non-op vehicle needs to be in the driveway not out on the street. Ok my bad, how do I get it back? She tells me I need to come by in the morning to get a release that the tow company will need to get my car released to me. I then call the tow company that towed it. Spoke with their dispatch guy who said yes they have the car and that the fees would be $383.00 to get it out. I would need to come tomorrow (Saturday to get it before 5pm which would be 24 hours since it was towed).
Saturday morning I go to Ontario PD and get the release form. Shows the car was towed at 4:50pm. That is important. Why? because according to Dietz Towing after 5pm they are closed and if I had the ability to come get it I would have to pay $100 more because it was after hours. Keep in mind I cannot go get it because I have to wait till Saturday morning to get the release from the Ontario PD. Also, because I have no opportunity to get the car that night, they charge an additional $53 dollars of storage because it is considered the next calendar day.
Saturday afternoon after getting the release from the Ontario Police Department I get to Dietz Towing to pay the fees. The lady on the phone says wait outside till a driver comes out to talk to you. 45 min later a driver pulls into their business and then comes out. I give him the release the papers and he comes back and tells me the amount is now $535.00. I tell him no way. He says the computer tells him what is owed. An extra $100 gate fee because they are technically closed on Saturdays, and an extra $53 for storage fee.
So to sum up, within less than 24 hours my car was towed, released to me and towed back to my house and I paid $535.00 to Dietz towing.
I agree to the fact I caused this to happen in the first place due to having a non-op out on the city street in front of my house. However, shouldn't someone from the tow company come to the door and tell the owner they are taking the car, maybe if they are decent people give them the opportunity to move it into the driveway. No, they wouldn't do that because then they would not be able to collect any money, especially the extra $153.00 they get by picking it up just before closing time on a Friday.
My suggestion/complaint is two sided. One the amount I was over charged due to circumstance completely out of my control. The extra $100 for having to get it after hours, and the extra day storage of $53 because the car sat in their facility over night. The other side to my complaint is the shady practice of this company and it is being facilitated by the city of Ontario Police Department. Simply because you need to sub contract out a tow company.
I went to write a review on YELP about the company and found I am not the only one who has been scammed by this tow company.
I would love the opportunity to talk with someone about my experience and try and get the amount I believe I was overcharged for back. If getting my money back is not an option at least would like the #OntarioPD to consider not using this tow company to do the city's work.

< review>
This is a hard sell as there are so many places to choose from in this area.  But for 19$ you get a reasonable assortment of meats, they are pretty good quality and they are fairly generous with the portion they give you.  The brisket is good, the bullgogi is good (not the best), the other meats are good too.  Good service, kind employees.   Now, decor is very 1980s strict mall antique, but it has been around for some 20 years and they seems to like to keep that rundown ambience.   Go for the meat, the service, and the full belly after.<//review>

< Review>
Horrible...I should have listened to my gut instinct when I didn't see any Korean guests there on a Saturday night. The food was tasteless and the cuts of meat were terrible.  First time going there and customer service was horrible.  I usually don't say harsh things, but they ruined our night. Let's see... they charge for not eating all the meat brought to you, which is understandable... but for the brisket, they brought out nearly 3lbs of meat, which was hard to digest.
Looking past it, they use grates that stick to the food which look like they were bought at the 99 cent store... once the charcoal built up and there was a very large flame... Instead of changing to a clean grill which normal places usually do, they lift it up and add lettuce down below the grill to prevent flare ups. Yes you heard me right,  lettuce.  After the lettuce burned away and another flare up, many leaves of lettuce went down below. We couldn't believe it, asking if we were okay, I asked for a single piece of steak...it never came.  Then deciding to leave, I directly handed the man the water container, and said he'll bring more, but he never came back.

The entire restaurant was filled with Non-Korean customers...and I thought, if they own people won't even eat here this is a bad sign. I felt bad to all the "foreign guests" becsuse this is probably their interpretation of Korean BBQ. Little did they know that they were duped and the experience was lackluster.

Once again, I never write bad things about others... however I feel compelled to warn "foreign guests" to beware of this place.  I wish I could stand in front and tell people not to eat here... however with no wait, with more than enough available seating, Non-Korean guests kept walking through the door.

If you're reading this, don't even try to give it a shot, you'll seriously regret it and be out 36 dollars for the night. Go to Moon BBQ or any other Korean BBQ joint. Don't cry afterwards saying that I didn't warn you!<//Review>

<rate>5< /rate>< text>
Took my mom for her 1st experience in Korean BBQ. I've had it before in K-town but this place is better than most of the other ones I've been to.  They have a 9.99 steak , pork and chicken special during  week days , but we went for the 13.99 a plate which came with beef bulgogi,  spicy pork butt, pork belly &  individual small steaks for each patron. The kimchi was superb and so was the marinades and the quality of the meat. Place has plenty of parking and it is nestled in an unassuming shopping center, blink and you'll miss it. There is plenty of parking. Service was prompt and very friendly, they switch our grill constantly and kept bringing out more kimchi. A must if you are in the are and hungry for good Korean bbq.<//text>

< text>
The food and coffee were delicious. The service was excellent too. I had a western omelet.
It had ham, green peppers, and onions. It was good. They don't allow you to substitute toast for pancakes. You have to purchase a complete pancake order. They have indoor and outdoor seating. They also have a very large parking lot.</text>

<name>Tommy Vincent< /name>< text>
Stopped in here for breakfast during COVID on our way to the Zoo. We were staying in old town and wanted to sit down and eat a decent meal before we headed into the park. They had outdoor dining set up which was nice. Only downfall was the cold weather on this specific morning, but they can't control the weather and the food here was pretty good. Everything came out hot, and our server kept our drinks full. We all had a nice meal and this hit the spot before our adventure at the SD Zoo. Fueled up and ready to hike around! We will be back the next time we are in the area. Hopefully they will have indoor dining by then.</text>

<name>Nikki Wood</name><Time>1618791701033< /Time>< rating>

< review>
On several occasions I've went to Perry's and encountered rude staff. The waitress sat us down and my cup was cracked. I politely told her she let out a disgruntled sigh and replaced it. As I was reading the menu I found dried lettuce on my fork! After many attempts I flagged down our waitress and showed her. Same response and no apology. I'm a bit disgusted by this time. My husband says we've waited for so long let's just eat and leave. My husband and I order we eat our food, which was good. We proceed to exit and a young man is at the counter ringing us up reading a magazine or a paper  without even looking up says "Tip on the card"? My husband apparently put off by the encounter waits. The young man says it again without looking up. My husband again waits for him to look up. In a manner to suggest my husband is slow the young man says "TIP ON THE CARD"! My husband says not sure if you were talking to me or the magazine and says no no tip our service was terrible. He scoffs at my husband and we leave. Yes, they've been around for quite some time and the food is good, but the customer service is horrendous. We have not returned and refuse to do so. We work hard for our money and we spend it where we feel like valued customers. I'm still very put off by the dirty dishes and bad service.</review>

<Review>I've passed by and lived around the area but have never given them a try. Glad that I finally did. Cute cafe located off the 5 close to Old Town and Rosecrans. If I'm not mistaken I believe they've been open since the 80s. Our server was very nice and always checked up on us.

Food:
Bacon, Eggs and Fruits
Corned Beef Hash,  Eggs, Fruits and Side White Toast.

The bacon and eggs were good but the corned beef hash was delicious. The fruits were also plentiful. We washed it down with a nice hot coffee.

I got to go at Perry's. The Combo Fritata and biscuits and gravy. I dont have any pictures unfortunately.

The fritata is always amazing. I like normal omelettes but the fritata is just always better in my opinion. The biscuits and gravy are some of my favorite in San Diego.

For me Perry's is a breakfast place. They do serve lunch but I cant ever get enough of the stuff they serve for breakfast.

Is there better places? Maybe. I dont think so though. Thanks Perry's for being consistently amazing with amazing delicious food.< /Text>

<userid>111838517834424535021< /userid><user_name>Andrea Schell<//user_name><Date>1503168947762< /Date>< rate>
5<//rate>
< Review>
I just went for the first time and I already adore this place. The retro vibe, the quick and attentive staff, short wait for food, sugar and cream on the table. This place runs like a well oiled ship. Our table was bussed before we could blink our eyes after getting up. I had a waffle egg bacon combo. The waffle was very similar to Waffle House waffles from back east that I have been missing badly. My husband had a spinach frittata (that was not skimped with cheese in the least) with hash browns that I stole a bite of, his meal was very good. Our waitress made her rounds offering a coffee fill every time she passed our table. We were both seriously impressed and will be back soon.

I came back and tried more things. The biscuits are not flaky fluffy buttermilk biscuits, they're more crumbly like cornbread.

The chips and guacamole and really good. They make the chips to order. They were still hot and a little chewy on some parts.</Review>

<text>This place is fantastic. If you're nearby, just eat here. When we arrived there was a line out the door. I gave my name and party size and we went outside to wait. Not a great start to the first experience but boy was it worth it. Waitress was very nice and polite and while everything she did she did quickly she never seemed to not pay attention to us. This place has a very vintage diner feel to it and it was an awesome experience. Prices are what you'd expect for breakfast, but the food was some of the tastiest I've had in my life. I ordered the 2 eggs 2 bacon and 2 strawberry pancakes (subbed out the bacon for sausage) and they were some of the best pancakes I've had in my life. Long story short, if you're anywhere close to Perry's you need to eat here. You won't regret it<//text>< Pics>

<username>Phillip Burum<//username><date>1560620473948< /date><rating>3<//rating>< review>
This place was my go-to for a long time. Today reminds me why I stopped coming here.

Everything we ordered came cold. The banana pancakes are misleading, and should be called pancakes with a banana. Normally the babe would imply banana in the batter. Here it means there's a banana rolled up in your pancake, and then it'll be served in the least convenient shape possible.

My chorizo and eggs taste great, but my extra well done, extra crispy hash browns were probably steamed to death before being dropped in oil (not to fry, but to soak). It's frustrating.

The coffee was worth 3-stars on it's own because it's pretty good, but also wasn't warm enough.< /review>

The food was ok not really that great though just plain ole ok. The service was not all that great, maybe our waitress was having a bad day but she was very short with us and was fast to sort of just slide our food on the table and walk away. Again maybe it was her attitude due to a bad day but.  We will not be going back.   I really dislike leaving bad reviews but Perry's  in no way shape or form lived up to their sign out front that boasts they are the best breakfast in San Diego.  I felt like I was at Mel's diner (the t.v. show) but instead of getting served by Alice we got Flow on a bad day :(

We were really looking forward to trying this place out.   Oh well every little adventure doesn't have to always work out.   Now we can say we've been there done that and we can warn our friends :)<//review>

<date>1554485860764< /date>< Text>
We consider Perry's Cafe to be one of the premier breakfast restaurants in San Diego.  Our family has been dining here regularly for years.  Simply put, outstanding food (and great variety within the menu) and wonderful, personal service.  One rather simple example stands out - the home fries are still made on the grill at Perry's.  At so many other restaurants, they are the heat and serve type.  Also, any of their pancakes or waffles have that "made here" quality - as in a batter that is made from an in-house recipe rather than a mix from a chain.  Whether you choose an adventurous or traditional breakfast here, you will enjoy it!!< /Text>

<user>116404381005990794449</user><username>Natalie Blanchard<//username>< Time>

< Review>
We were visiting from Phoenix, Az and were looking for a good noncommercial breakfast spot. My cousin who lives in the area recommended Perry's.
We arrived around 12:30pm and when we pulled in there was a big group of people waiting outside! To most people, this would turn them away but I take this as a good sign!! More people = good food! It only took about 20 mins for our party of 5 to be seated.
Once we sat down we were greeted within minutes and our waitress took our drink order. She checked on us regularly to see if we were ready to order or if we had questions. I wish I remembered her name because she was very pleasant and attentive. Even on a very busy Sunday afternoon.
Now for the food... our table order 2 burgers, 2 pancake stacks, banana cakes, eggs and home fries. The easiest way to explain how good the good was, well.... I didn't get any pictures cause it was all gone before I could grab my phone lol! I got one of the burgers and it was a big juicy delicious burger. I couldn't help but sneak a bite of my son's pancakes and then I almost ate half of them haha. Some of the best pancakes I've had. The quality and quantity of each one of our plates was worth every minute waiting and every penny we spent. Come hungry, leave stuffed!
I definitely recommend this place! Sorry, no pictures.</Review>

I have been a customer of Perry's for nearly 20 years now. Love this place, a true old school San Diego establishment. The food is not fancy, just your typical American diner food. Being in San Diego is has both standard American fare and Mexican food. Every breakfast plate can be ordered Mexican style with beans n tortillas instead of potatoes n toast. They recently remodeled the entire inside to bring the decor out of the 70's and the results are very good. This is a great spot for locals or visitors this fine city. Located across the street from the Old Towne Trollly stop, so it is easy to get to with or without a car. Be sure to check it out!</Text>

<name>Joel Jervis<//name><Time>1443779134950< /Time><Rating>5</Rating>< review>
'm a fan.
Whatever you order, you can rest assured knowing that it's A LOT of food. I ordered breakfast basics: Pecan Waffle, scrambled eggs, and bacon.  My friend ordered biscuits and gravy, scalloped fried potatoes, bacon and eggs and wasn't able to finish it. So of course I was happy to help!
Prices are relatively cheap and the service is extremely friendly!

Stayed at the Hilton on the previous night but upon waking one should ask him/her self. "Do I 'really' want to eat breakfast at the HIlton or should I try to experience a San Diego breakfast at a 'mom and pop' store elsewhere?" Answering that question correctly has the power to improve your experience.< /review>

< Date>
1426610110775<//Date>
<username>Paul Chintawat< /username>< Rate>
3< /Rate>
< review>
I wanted to find a breakfast place that I could go to that would satisfy my breakfast urges.  I thought Perry's was going to be it.  The food was average.  There were so many frittatas to choose from.  There are also omelettes, french toast, pancakes.  Be careful, when they say strawberry or banana pancakes, that doesn't mean they are mixed in the batter.  The pancakes are just topped with the fruit.

A major concern that I had was the wait.  Start the stopwatch.. sit down at the table, place your order, wait for your food.  Stop the clock.  That was a little over an hour.  I'm not including the time that we waited to get our table.  We had a group of seven people, so there were more orders, but there were tables of five and six people, ordering after us and getting their food before us.

I was fine with the wait for the table, the place is popular.  But waiting over an hour to get our food once we've sat, is not acceptable to me.

This was my first visit, so I may be willing to give it one more shot.<//review>

< user_name>
Char Aznable< /user_name>
<Date>1469931370554</Date><Rating>5<//Rating><gmapID>0x80deaae66a57ce09:0xa4b7d84047ea47c6<//gmapID><pics>None< /pics>< user>
113394025331994732964< /user>
<Review>This restaurant is not "retro" in the sense that it was styled in retro decorative fashion. It's original architecture. That is what makes it unique to the "throwback" diner themes that many would flock to. This is original architecture for this restaurant, and it you can't get that in today's cookie cutter Denny's franchises dotted thruout the U.S. On every freeway exit.

The food comes to you hot. Not lukewarm just barely served, but steaming off the griddle, and steam as in rich visible steam. The hash browns aren't just dumped from a box. They use a real old-fashion cast iron ironing iron to flatten out the hash browns to cook with. Hot fluffy eggs and actual pipping hot coffee. Awesomely fluffy pancakes.

This is not the diner you will see in the movies, this diner is best reserved for those that enjoy an excellent meal without all the movie tie-in nonsense of an IHOP or Denny's.< /Review></record>

<Text>My friend April suggested we go to Perry's, as she had never been, and always wanted to have breakfast there. I had been once with my daughter, a year prior, and the food was standard diner fare. So we went, with her adorable 9 mo. old baby in tow. Jack is eminently good natured, and on this particular occasion was finding his voice, and making gleeful shrieking sounds. About 15 min. into our breakfast experience, having ordered and gotten coffee, a gruff older man, a customer on his way up to the cashier, rudely told us that is we couldnt control the baby, we should leave the restaurant. This began an unruly, and fairly loud, exchange between the man and myself. As he walked away, leaving us shocked, yet another customer, also an older man, told us we should leave. My friend April was reduced to tears, and I was outraged. She wanted to leave immediately, and explained this to our server, who made no effort to console her or stop us from leaving. The manager  on site was evidently oblivious to the entire incident. Because I did not want to further distress my friend, I left quietly with her. But I am dismayed and disgusted by the whole experience. Apparently Perry's is not a family friendly establishment, but a place for crusty old people to dine without being bothered by the joyful sounds of happy babies. I can say from previous experience that the food here is average. The menu is exactly what you would expect. The staff, patrons, and environment were an abysmal experience, and I would recommend Perry's to no one.< /Text>< Pictures>

< text>
We were just starting to google a search for a nice place to go for breakfast. As we rounded the corner off Taylor St., there is was in huge letters: "The Breakfast Place", almost like divine intervention! The service was very friendly, engaging, and attentive! Nicole was our server. Even though it was our first time there, she made us feel like we were long time, favorite customers. She described the food and portions, which the restaurant is known for. The menu was unique with unusual, but VERY tasty options, in additional to traditional breakfast choices. The atmosphere was a quaint time capsule out of the 70's, but fit just right! We got our food pretty fast, even though it was fairy busy. I wanted to customize my fritatta order with some extra ingredients to compliment the fantastic original recipe. Anything goes, and Nicole added the goodies! The coffee was fresh and VERY good! Our orders came and we were amazed! Huge portions and absolutely delicious, just as Nicole had described! She brought us extra napkins, and we blasted off into breakfast bliss! We will DEFINITELY make Perry's Cafe a gotta have it destination on our next trip to San Diego!
~ Jerry & Trina~</text>

<Pictures>None<//Pictures><response>None<//response><name>Amy Davis</name>< text>
Great price, great food, excellent service. The place is always buzzing with people, a sure fire sign its a rocking joint. The entire inside looks like it was built in the 60s, this isnt a negative as it has been extremely well maintained giving it a great atmosphere. The kitchen is open and in view and the cooking staff is very well kept and maintained. The food selection is very wide and for the price you cannot beat it. The coffee is always hot and has a great taste. All in all I highly recommend this place as one of the hidden gems of san diego.<//text>

<GmapID>0x80deaae66a57ce09:0xa4b7d84047ea47c6<//GmapID><name>Steve Schwartz</name><response>None< /response>< Text>
UPDATE 8/18 - Someone must have paid attention, because, except for the weird men's room layout, everything seems to be fixed. The potatoes are great, waitstaff seem to be on track, and all's right in the universe! Nice to see a great breakfast joint actually respond to their customers. Updated to four stars, back in my breakfast rotation.

--------------

The definition of insanity is doing the same thing over and over, and expecting different results. Eating here repeatedly, with modest expectations, qualifies me for the rubber room. Awful food, server couldn't remember what planet she was on, let alone how to serve the meal... can't emphasize enough the poor food quality. Potatoes sit on the grill, burning in their predecessor's carbon, imparting a burnt, unhealthy flavor to what gets served. Carne asada was like shoe leather, and the 'ranchero sauce' was some rendition of celery, onion, and tomato, simmered on a warmer. Nothing fresh about any of it.

Too bad, because before the owner passed, they were a really decent breakfast house. Now, suitable for the locals who don't know any better. Feh.

Oh, yeah. In the men's room, the urinal is right next to the sink, where, hopefully, some folks wash their hands. THERE IS NO PARTITION/BARRIER, so you are literally looking right at the bowl when using the sink, and whatever dangly bits may be availing of same. Disgusting is too kind a word for this...just a simple metal partition is apparently too much to ask. Attn: health department.

There are a few good servers there - and I'll miss them...done with this joint.< /Text>

< userid>
101555400167634699766< /userid>
<user_name>Nick Marksberry</user_name>< Time>
1436717801314< /Time>
<Rate>1</Rate>< review>
We're from out of town, so we were just looking for a quick cafe place to grab breakfast at. Google maps says "known for their breakfast" for Perrys Cafe so we gave it a shot.

Staff wasn't very friendly. The guy who seated us greeted us with a smile to start and simply walked away grumbling something when we got to the table.

The prices were pretty high as well for a cafe. My wife got steak and eggs for $12.50, which isn't bad. I ordered from the al a carte menu 2 eggs for $3.50, bacon for $3.75, and a bowl of oatmeal for $3.25. See the prices I expected some decent food. The bacon was burnt when it came out, and the oatmeal seems to have been pulled from a huge pot that sits all morning. I wasn't expecting 5 star, but if you are going to charge $1 for a piece of bacon, at least cook it right. Very unhappy with our trip there.<//review>

<Text>Perry's Cafe has been serving San Diego for as long as I can remember.  My last memory at this location on Pacific Hwy. I was enjoying a stack of pancakes with my belated Father, over 30 years ago.

<Rating>2</Rating>< text>
Went with a group of eight and although I am not big on greasy spoon restaurants, we had out of town visitors that wanted exactly that, so we gave Perry's a try.  I ordered the Mexican eggs benedict, which were Aweful!  Canadian bacon was over cooked and dry, not worth cutting into, the sauce was out of a can or bottle, but definitely not a good tasting one.  I asked for hashbrowns instead of beans and those were decent.  The best part of my dish was probably the eggs, but had to clean as much of the sauce off as possible.  The waitress was nice, but busy and got my husband's tortillas wrong.  He describes his meal as ok, but wouldn't order it again.  If you are going to serve mexican food in San Diego, it should be at the very least decent.</text>

< review>
Went ther today, It's been awhile... (we usually like to make breakfast at home) and I keep forgetting about the place. Anyway.. I had the spinach, bacon, mushroom fritatta, and my wife had the mexican fritatta (macha). Cut them in half and had a great breakfast. Ordered the home fries, which were good but could have used some additions.. like onions and chilies.. I asked if they had good sourdough and was told "not so much" so I got the blueberry muffins.... I don't know what they were thinking or if today was normal, but they were the worst.. My first bite just turned to dough in my mouth.. had to spit it out. But... I will definatly go back... just avoid the muffins ;O)
bob<//review>
